					<h4>Western Book Roundup</h4>
		
		<h1>Wild West for Book Industry</h1>
		<h2><i></i></h2>
		<div class="text-feature_print">
							<p>By Jenny Shank, 1-14-09</p>
			
			
							<p>A lot has happened in the book world since the last Roundup I wrote before heading off on maternity leave in November, <a target="_blank" href="http://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/04/business/04publish.html?_r=1&amp;ref=opinion" title="not much of it good">not much of it good</a>.&nbsp; In December, Random House and Simon &amp; Schuster announced layoffs and staff reorganizations, and Houghton Mifflin, a press with a long history of publishing Western writers (including A.B. Guthrie, Jr., Willa Cather, and, more recently, <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/an_interview_with_molly_gloss/C131/L39/" title="Molly Gloss">Molly Gloss</a>), announced a freeze on acquiring new books. Can you see the tumbleweeds a&#8217; blowing down the bookstore aisle?
</p>
<p>
Closer to home, Scripps offered the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/dec/04/rocky-mountain-news-sale/" title="Rocky Mountain News for sale">Rocky Mountain News for sale</a> and announced the paper would be shuttered if a buyer wasn&#8217;t found within a few weeks.&nbsp; I&#8217;ve written <a target="_blank" href="http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/entertainment/books/" title="book reviews for the Rocky Mountain News">book reviews for the Rocky Mountain News</a> for eight years, so I&#8217;m partial, but even after repeated cuts in the section&#8217;s allotted space (the book section now runs <I>behind</I> the professional wrestling column), the Rocky&#8217;s book section was one of the best in the region, featuring local reviewers&#8217; takes on national and regional books and editor Patti Thorn&#8217;s witty, entertaining columns and features.&nbsp; (By contrast, much of the Denver Post&#8217;s books section, apart from Colorado writer David Milofsky&#8217;s insightful column, is filled with wire stories by freelancers from elsewhere.)
</p>
<p>
The book industry looks like it&#8217;s shrinking, as publishers, bookstores, and book review sections and the newspapers that house them falter.&nbsp; But I take comfort in the fact that there are still plenty of people who enjoy books as much as I do&#8212;a lot fewer of them than in the past, sure&#8212;but true book lovers are not going to stop reading any time soon.&nbsp; In this century, book lovers might become the equivalent of devotees of the harpsichord and the autogyro&#8212;our heyday has past, but I believe we make up in enthusiasm what we lack in numbers.&nbsp; (Witness the Oregon parents who <a target="_blank" href="http://www.powells.com/blog/?p=4168" title="recently named their child after Powell's bookstore">recently named their child after Powell&#8217;s bookstore</a>.)  And I am not going to stop reading any time soon.
</p>
<p>
We&#8217;re in a sort of wild West for media right now&#8212;people are shifting away from reading printed books and periodicals, and reading more such content online.&nbsp; Nobody wants to pay for anything they read on the Internet, which spells trouble for people who make their living from writing and publishing.&nbsp; But just as lawless Western territories were eventually reigned in, this too will settle out.&nbsp; And like everybody else, I just wish I could guess where it was going.
</p>
<p>
Other book news I noticed in between diaper changes: 
</p>
<p>
Denver hung tough in the annual <a target="_blank" href="http://www.ccsu.edu/amlc08/overall_10.htm" title="survey of the most literate cities">survey of the most literate cities</a>, dropping from fourth place last year to the still-respectable seventh place.&nbsp; Other Western cities in the top ten this year: Seattle (2), San Francisco (5), and Portland (10.5).
</p>
<p>
Boulder writer and psychologist <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/20843/C39/L39/" title="Doreen Orion">Doreen Orion</a> spoke with the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/07/fashion/07clubs.html?_r=1&amp;ref=fashion" title="New York Times">New York Times</a> about a book club gone bad because of one &#8220;drama queen who turned every meeting into her own personal therapy session.&#8221;
</p>
<p>
Westminster, Colo.-based literary superstar <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/an_interview_with_david_wroblewski/C39/L39/" title="David Wroblewski">David Wroblewski</a> announced he&#8217;s <a target="_blank" href="http://www.salon.com/wires/ap/entertainment/2008/12/18/D9559L480_books_more_sawtelle/" title="working on a prequel">working on a prequel</a> to his massive success, <I>The Story of Edgar Sawtelle</I>.&nbsp; The Denver Post offered a new profile of Wroblewski, and he&#8217;ll hit the big time on an <a target="_blank" href="http://www.oprah.com/entity/oprahsbookclub" title="Oprah's Book Club">Oprah&#8217;s Book Club</a> episode that airs January 26.
</p>
<p>
Finally, Jack Shakely offered <a target="_blank" href="http://internetreviewofbooks.com/dec08/tony_hillerman_essay.html" title="this appreciation">this appreciation</a> of the late, great Tony Hillerman for the Internet Review of Books.
</p>
<p>
I&#8217;m officially back in the saddle again, dear readers (and I&#8217;m packing along two kids on the book trail these days), so please <script type="text/javascript">
